	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><b>uber</b><br />
<b>casual</b><br />
<br />
Qhilw I basically agree with Istari, in both cases that these are merely descriptions, and vagueness is not technically a problem in many cases.  However, I agree with Loral that these two terms are WAY overused.  He's not talking about &quot;Nice sword, uber.&quot;  He's talking about people on message boards in lower level guilds using the word &quot;uber&quot; to apply to such a vast number of players in a context that demands more accuracy.  The same thing happens in reverse with casuals.  People toss around the word &quot;casual&quot; and the word &quot;uber&quot; in attempts to categorize large numbers of people, and almost invariably convey a ridiculous stereotype instead.  The real problem is not that &quot;casual&quot; and &quot;uber&quot; are vague, it's that people too often cross the line from vagueness to stereotype.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Mudflation</b><br />
<br />
Mudflation is not a meaningless term, and in my experience it is only slightly overused and doesn't carry quite the &quot;negativity&quot; that Loral seems to want to associate with it.  Yeah it is a negative, but it's also something most players accept and do understand the benefits (if you try hard enough you can find them praising those benefits).<br />
<br />
<i>Few describe exactly what they mean when they use the term and fewer can describe how to fix it. The game gets larger. The high-end zones get higher. Level limits increase. Equipment grows in power. That isn't mudflation, that's progress.</i><br />
<br />
I say exactly what I mean by mudflation.  And generally when I refer to its negatives I am concerned with two things.  It ruins older content by unbalancing challenge and incentives, and ruins item individuality, which affects new and old content alike.<br />
<br />
Mudflation occurs where items never leave the economy, never deteriorate, and for the most part perpetually decrease in value.  This is exacerbated by &quot;expansion-flation,&quot; a type of mudflation where certian qualities of items become far easier to obtain simply by virtue of spending $45 on an expansion.  As mentioned, this has two consequences.<br />
<br />
The first is that eventually, people are more powerful for the content designed for them than they were intended to be.  Sometimes, this doesn't mean a whole lot, players just move ahead and advance a little more quickly through certian stages of the game than was originally intended.  Often, though, what happens is that people do the same encounters, except now they're a lot easier... yet still yield the same rewards.  Where mobs previously would go green, forcing players to face other challenges, mobs stay blue and players can stay right where they are for easy, low-risk advancement.  <br />
<br />
And some content becomes underused altogether because items decrease in value so far, it becomes not worth the effort to obtain them.  That's not progress, that's marginalization of old content.  Progress is gearing yourself in planar armor so that you can fight in Kael to gear yourself for Temple of Veeshan to gear yourself for Sleepers Tomb and the North Wing, so that you can fight in Luclin and PoP etc.  That is progression.  Mudflation is a first-time level 52 warrior so well-equipped with bazaar gear that he can solo Karnor's with ease.  Mudflation is when that soloing warrior lets rare items, once prized and valuable, rot because better stuff drops constantly in the new expansion and can be purchased in the bazaar for a pittance.  There is no excitement for that warrior, he is just grinding xp as quickly as he can so he can catch up to the parts of the game not yet mudflated beyond recognition.<br />
<br />
The second serious problem mudflation causes is an overabundance of items and an upgrade pattern that is too rapid, to the point that the game begins to feel like a treadmill.  Instead of feeling as if you are on a perpetual search for more power and advancement, you begin to regocnize the cyclic pattern of gear-fight-gear-fight.  That pattern is always there, but when items come into the economy so easily and in such great quantities that cheap upgrades are always available, you just notice it more.<br />
<br />
Thsi is why Everquest has taken steps to curb mudflation, though not too many, largely because of the the fundamental design of the game.  Item deterioration, for example, is not compatible with EQ.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Timesink</b><br />
<br />
Timesink does, in fact, mean something.  It means <i>almost</i> exactly what he says it means:<br />
<br />
&quot;Timesinks describe any action in Everquest that someone doesn't enjoy.&quot;<br />
<br />
More accurately, a timesink is a repetitive activity that takes a significant period of time, is not fun, but is required for advancement.  Reading a book is a timesink, only if the book is not enjoyable and you are only reading it because you have to for some reason.  Otherwise, it's more accurately called a &quot;passtime.&quot;  EQ has rewards, and it puts obstacles in front of these rewards.  The fun of the game is overcoming these obstacles.  When one of these obstacles is excessively unfun, and takes a long time to defeat, then it is properly called a <b>timesink</b>.  When something takes a long time to accomplish, but the interim is fun, then it is a passtime.<br />
<br />
Obviously, there is some subjectivity here, but a certian leniency should be granted in an informal discussion.  If someone quits EQ citing an overabundance of &quot;timesinks,&quot; you can assume that they simply found no way to get to the parts of the game they enjoyed without being forced to endure excessive periods of boring play.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Loral</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Before you begin telling me that you HAVE to camp shards to get intoVex Thal or you HAVE to get your Ring of Scale faction up, remember that this entire game is voluntary and the world is big enough to find a million other and often more enjoyable things to do.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>But really, some people play EQ for the excitement of getting into new zones and overcoming the hardest content in the game.  There's nothing else that they enjoy.  &quot;Have&quot; is technically an exaggeration, but it's really just short for &quot;this is what I want.&quot;  &quot;I need to get to Vex Thal but I h8 the timesinks&quot; really means &quot;I want to get to Vex Thal, because there is nothing else in the game that interests me: why is the key quest so long and boring?&quot;<br />
<br />
Timesink, though it does get misused fairly frequently, IS a word with an important meaning.  It is not meaningless.  It is not an &quot;overused generality.&quot;  It's an accurate description of a frequent problem with Everquest.<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Class Balance</b><br />
<br />
He is wrong, here.  Going by the technical definition, classes for sure can be balanced.  Balance occurs when different classes can perform different functions but still be similarly effective.  In reality, Perfect Class Balance is never achieved, but it's not completely impossible and it is most certianly something that is worth working towards.  That most people who argue about Class Balance are clueless of the actual state of the game, or are partisan liars deliberately exaggerating in hopes of getting freebies for their class, doesn't mean that Class Balance is not a worthy goal.<br />
<br />
Also, while perhaps not quite the most accurate term, &quot;Class Balance Concern&quot; has often been the name given to specific problems with a class itself, without reference to any other classes.  Complaining about a worthless AA ability, for example, will often be considered a &quot;Class Balance&quot; debate but in reality it is just a specific concern about a specific ability.  But it's not really &quot;wrong&quot; to call it class balance either, and skirting around the terms isn't really going t ohelp anything.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
