	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>I think the 'perfect class balance' point is a tricky one because you can only have perfect balance if you have a clear-cut idea of how powerful abilities are. but how strong is mage focus summon? early on, my guild got a big boost from this spell as we lacked foci but now the spell does nothing on a raid. how do you value something that is contingently useful like this?<br />
<br />
one option is just to resolve it all into terms of kill speed / xp bonuses. this improves things somewhat but it's still sticky and contingent. it's these variables that make the idea of perfect balance tricky, because a player for instance can choose to do something which makes class x more powerful than class y all the time instead of going to a place where y &gt; x.<br />
<br />
still, those variables only stretch so far so a fuzzy idea of class balance is possible. SKs and Pals at one point were basically seen as equals and even just referred to as 'hybrids' with no preference- ie we need to get a hybrid for this group. they weren't exactly equal of course but were generally seen as such with good justification.<br />
<br />
it's like seeing a line drawn on paper and seeing it as a perfectly straight line. it's not- only the geometric form is- but it's good enough for us. that's sort of like how class balance is if you can even have the perfect idea. but anyone who looks at said line will say it's good enough, and like classes- that's all you really need.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
		<img class="inlineimg" src="images/statusicon/user_offline.gif" alt="Istari is offline" border="0" />


		
		
		
		&nbsp;
	</td>
