	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>English is an adaptive language and slang expressions for new things are imaginative and create a mental picture that sometimes makes it's way to describe more than what it was originally intended for and become part of the general language.<br />
<br />
From &quot;learning the ropes&quot; (an old British Navy term) to &quot;Slacker&quot; and &quot;Shoddy&quot; (Civil War terms), there is a rich history of how some of our words and expressions started. There was a multi-part series some time back on PBS called the English Language hosted by Robert McNeil that was wonderful to watch...a real history of the language and just how adaptive it is. I highly recommend it if you can get a copy of it.<br />
<br />
So when I see terms like Timesink, Uber, or other slang words, it is simply English adapting to our changing and evolving world. I see this as a good thing, and indicates that English is not stagnant, but thriving and growing.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
