					&nbsp;<br /><a href="member.php?s=e10c32f9b81222ced0da9d7bbae5d802&amp;u=158"><img src="image.php?s=e10c32f9b81222ced0da9d7bbae5d802&amp;u=158&amp;dateline=1072741795" alt="Istari's Avatar" border="0" /></a>
				</div>
			
			
			<div class="smallfont">
				&nbsp;<br />
<div>
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=428406" target="blank">Magelo Profile</a></div>

<div>Join Date: Jun 2003</div>
				
				<div>
					
					
				</div>
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>all languages are adaptive. in the pre-modern periods, languages would change rapidly because people did not have a model to follow. old english is barely readable to an uninitiated person of today, and middle english is a severe pain in the ass. education makes things more interesting. take 'ya'll' for example. english doesn't have a second person plural such as the spanish vosotros or latin tui, in its &quot;proper&quot; form. education teaches us that ya'll is slang. language is adaptive, though, so ya'll has emerged in a number of places, but the &quot;proper&quot; english stamps this out.<br />
<br />
demanding specificity of language is stupid though. take some following examples:<br />
<br />
1) You have a pile of sand that weighs 400lbs. a grain of sand is going to be removed every quarter of a second. at which point does the pile of sand cease to be a pile? do we need to refer to the sand by its mass? but then we'd need to load the stuff onto a scale. this is clearly not feasible for people who want to talk about sand. so I might refer to a 'pile of sand' which another person might not think of as a pile of sand at all, but perhaps some different sort of quantity.<br />
<br />
2) You're talking about different kinds of cars- describing them to people. this involves describing some of them as fast. certainly you could say that both a mustang and a ferrari are fast- but the ferrari is obviously much faster. anyone who hears of a 'fast ferrari' with some knowledge about it should know the difference between that and a 'fast mustang'. the adjective here is also dependent on its noun. even though the individual terms are vague, they can be referential and thus absolutely specific.<br />
<br />
this might be kind of odd at glance, but once a term becomes a reference it becomes a symbolic identity. let's say that you have a concept of a specific item set:<br />
<br />
a pair of black nike sandals that are worn out. the bottoms are covered with mud and the strap is barely hanging on by a string.<br />
<br />
all of this can be referred to by &quot;my sandals&quot; and this stands for the said object. in fact, we could go further and detail the material composition, the physics of the object, its entire history- we could write a book on these shoes and all of this can be represented by 2 simple words. by the same token, those two words out of a context can be taken to mean billions of different items. this is exactly what loral does when he evaluates these words out of context, and it's why (again) the article is stupid. any crack-brained moron with EQ experience can tell what uber, timesink etc mean in the context of a post because these words represent a set of identities and posters usually make clear what they're talking about in the post.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
